<div id="review_12134098" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/12134098" />
    <a title="Ray" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/765636-ray"><img alt="Ray" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546566068p2/765636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/12134098?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ray" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ray" href="/user/show/765636-ray">Ray</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/765636-ray?shelf=novels">novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/765636-ray?shelf=conspiracy">conspiracy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/765636-ray?shelf=audio">audio</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer12134098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13788804376527071431">It goes without saying that Foucault&apos;s Pendulum is one of the most profound novels I&apos;ve ever read, and is more relevant than ever in these conspiratorial times. <br/><br/>Eco&apos;s expertise in the realm of all things occult is astounding, and even more so as he criticizes the fields of &quot;Neo-Templarism&quot; and secret societies which portend to have historical merit and try to influence the world by way of obscure publishing. Then there is the saga of the game which goes out of control, simply amazing writing. Mu</span>
  <span id="freeText13788804376527071431" style="display:none">It goes without saying that Foucault's Pendulum is one of the most profound novels I've ever read, and is more relevant than ever in these conspiratorial times. <br /><br />Eco's expertise in the realm of all things occult is astounding, and even more so as he criticizes the fields of "Neo-Templarism" and secret societies which portend to have historical merit and try to influence the world by way of obscure publishing. Then there is the saga of the game which goes out of control, simply amazing writing. Much to be learned from this. <br /><br />However, in this review I have to critique the abridged audiobook edition. Expertly read by Tim Curry, the acting is excellent and a great intellectual European vibe fitting for the tone of the book. But the only thing is, it's far too short. A tale of this complexity shouldn't be abridged, it should take as many dozens of hours necessary. I suppose it's a good edit as these things go, and I commend whomever is in charge of that for shortening the story to a mere seven and a half or so hours, but apparently I am too much of an purist so not the intended audiences. And, guess the famous actors who narrate won't do unabridged... <br /><br />Still, it is a powerful read and highly recommended. The most literary of the conspiracy theory novel subgenre, with an important moral to not take such things too seriously lest we go mad. Good advice these days indeed. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13788804376527071431" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


