  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3965412918" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3965412918" />
    <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera"><img alt="Inderjit Sanghera" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564826235p2/900800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3965412918?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Inderjit Sanghera" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Inderjit Sanghera" href="/user/show/900800-inderjit-sanghera">Inderjit Sanghera</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3965412918" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10589023966301263651">Eco’s novel, whose principle characters are a group of ponderous paranoiacs, swings between being unreadable due to its preoccupation with esoterica and preponderously brilliant and witty. Perhaps that is how Eco designed the novel, as he depicts the chaos causes by the descent of a group of literati who turn the ramblings of a monomaniac into a giant global conspiracy, half in jest and half in seriousness, the reprecussions of which are dire and even deadly for the characters. It can be difficu</span>
  <span id="freeText10589023966301263651" style="display:none">Eco’s novel, whose principle characters are a group of ponderous paranoiacs, swings between being unreadable due to its preoccupation with esoterica and preponderously brilliant and witty. Perhaps that is how Eco designed the novel, as he depicts the chaos causes by the descent of a group of literati who turn the ramblings of a monomaniac into a giant global conspiracy, half in jest and half in seriousness, the reprecussions of which are dire and even deadly for the characters. It can be difficult to really get a feel for the characters, as they appear to be permanently on the cusp of one madcap scheme to another. Instead the joy of the novel comes from exploring the riddle which the characters build and which is swiftly dismantled by Belbo’s fiancée, the feeling of paranoia which gradually builds is quickly destroyed by the reality of the narrative Belbo and his friends have concocted.<br /><br />In many ways Eco’s novel and the themes it explores is prescient in a world where disinformation and conspiracies have never been more widespread and easy to disseminate. Eco uncovers the truth behind most conspiracy theorists, that they are in essence just a banal group of individuals, whose ideas amount to nothing more than tedious theorizing and connecting dots which don’t exist. Eco’s novel is at its weakest when it get lost in its own sense of whimsy and at its best when it exposes the stupidity of its characters.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10589023966301263651" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

